                <p>
                    I was raised in Montana, where nature was always a big part of my life. I grew up camping, fishing, rock climbing, floating, and spending a lot of time outdoors. As I got into high school, I spent less and less time outside engaging in the experiences that had brought me so much joy. My mental health declined significantly. It got so severe that my family sent me away to a residential treatment center where I lived for three months receiving intensive behavioral health therapy. This experience changed my life and informed my decision to study psychology. While I was in treatment, my favorite part of everyday was when I got to go outside, hear the sound of the quaking aspens rustle in the wind, and feel the sun on my face.
